  "text": "ð∂T ph ∕∂ϕÞ x ¼ −ð∂T ph ∕∂xÞ ϕ ð∂x∕∂ϕÞ T ph [CITATION_1] In Fig. 4 , we observe that ð∂T ph ∕∂xÞ ϕ is always negative. Thus, according to Eq. 1, ð∂x∕∂ϕÞ T ph and ð∂T ph ∕∂ϕÞ x always have the same sign, and ð∂x∕∂ϕÞ T ph must be equal to zero when ð∂T ph ∕∂ϕÞ x is equal to zero. Thus, the line of maxima of the cloud point curves coincides with the line where the binodal curves have maxima. This \"ridge line\" on the coexistence surface is shown as the red dashed line in Fig. 4 . On the lower ϕ side of the ridge line, both ð∂x∕∂ϕÞ T ph and ð∂T ph ∕∂ϕÞ x are positive. On the higher ϕ side, these two derivatives are both negative. Interestingly, in the low ϕ region ðϕ < ∼0.1Þ, T ph with good accuracy is a linear function of x, as shown in Fig. 5 . The extrapolation of T ph to 100% βB1 solution, i.e., x ¼ 1, agrees well with T ph ¼ 249AE 2 K of pure βB1 solutions [CITATION_2] .",
